				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Kasumi wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">As for avoiding clc and sec, it can indeed save you a lot of cycles in loops. clc/sec before a loop instead of during every iteration is simple enough.</div>
<br />This is strategic use of such optimizations, which is usually a net benefit. It reduces clarity of the optimized routine, but frees up cycles so that the <em>rest</em> of your code can be clearer and not have to be as optimized.
<br />
<br />My main point was that you can make the most impact with a given amount of your time by spending some/most of it at the end. At that time, you have the big picture and can consider high-level changes that make a big impact, or clarity-reducing low-level optimizations where they provide the most impact (like in a division routine).</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

